\par }{\b\f4\insrsid10294001 
\par Download Installation Files
\par ------------------------------------------------------
\par }{\f4\insrsid10294001 OpenClinica runs and depends on several external applications: Sun's Java Development Kit, Apache Jakarta's Tomcat Servlet Container, and the Postgres Relational Database.
\par }{\b\f4\insrsid10294001 
\par }{\f4\insrsid10294001 At Akaza Research we keep a copy of the setup files for tomcat, postgres and java located at the link below. Note there are 32bit and 64bit editions when applicable, also these are the exact versi
ons we test with. Our software may work with other versions of the applications but have not been tested.
\par 
\par http://svn.akazaresearch.com/oc/software/OpenClinica-3.1/
\par 
\par Below are some quick wget lines for 32bit and 64bit software needed for the installation. 
\par 
\par To determine if you are on a 32bit or 64bit OS run "uname -a" in your terminal, if you see "i386" or "i686" you are on a 32bit OS, if you see "x86_64" you are on a 64bit OS.
\par 
\par Run the following command for your architecture to download the files on your server.
\par 
\par \tab mkdir -p /usr/local/oc/install 
\par \tab cd /usr/local/oc/install
\par 
\par }{\b\f4\insrsid10294001 Now run the 32bit or 64bit commands below depending on your architecture. }{\f4\insrsid10294001 
\par 
\par }{\b\f4\insrsid10294001 32BIT}{\f4\insrsid10294001 
\par \tab wget http://svn.akazaresearch.com/oc/software/OpenClinica-3.1/linux/apache-tomcat-6.0.32.tar.gz
\par \tab wget http://svn.akazaresearch.com/oc/software/OpenClinica-3.1/linux/jdk-6u24-linux-i586.bin
\par 
\par }{\b\f4\insrsid10294001 if you are using oracle you do not need to download the postgres install file below.}{\f4\insrsid10294001 
\par \tab wget http://svn.akazaresearch.com/oc/software/OpenClinica-3.1/linux/postgresql-8.4.1-1-linux.bin
\par 
\par }{\b\f4\insrsid10294001 64BIT}{\f4\insrsid10294001 
\par \tab wget http://svn.akazaresearch.com/oc/software/OpenClinica-3.1/linux/apache-tomcat-6.0.32.tar.gz
\par \tab wget http://svn.akazaresearch.com/oc/software/OpenClinica-3.1/linux/jdk-6u24-linux-x64.bin
\par }{\b\f4\insrsid10294001 if you are using oracle you do not need to download the postgres install file below.}{\f4\insrsid10294001 
\par \tab wget http://svn.akazaresearch.com/oc/software/OpenClinica-3.1/linux/postgresql-8.4.1-1-linux-x64.bin
\par 
\par You can download all the files needed to install tomcat, postgres and java from that URL or wget statements above or you can go and download the files from the individual vendors. Links to each vendors websites are below.
\par 
\par Postgres - http://www.postgresql.org/
\par Java - http://www.oracle.com/technetwork/java/index.html
\par Tomcat - http://tomcat.apache.org/
\par 
\par To obtain the OpenClinica 3.1 software itself you can download that on our openclinica.com website from the following URL.
\par 
\par https://community.openclinica.com/project/openclinica
\par 
\par Note: A free community account is needed and you will be prompted to login to access the download.
\par 
\par Once downloaded please move it into the "/usr/local/oc/install" directory we created and downloaded the other software into.
\par 
\par }{\b\f4\insrsid10294001 FOR THE REMAINDER OF THE DOCUMENT I WILL NOT BE USING EXACT FILENAMES AS THESE NEXT STEPS CAN BE USED FOR EITHER 32BIT OR 64BIT. PLEASE FILL IN THE FILENAME AS NEEDED FOR YOUR ARCHITECTURE.
\par 
\par Install Java
\par ------------------------------------------------------
\par }{\f4\insrsid10294001 You should already be in "/ust/local/oc/install" if not cd into it now via the command below.
\par \tab cd /usr/local/oc/install
\par Now run the following to install java.
\par \tab chmod a+x jdk-6*
\par \tab ./jdk-6*
\par Once done extracting and you see "Press Enter to continue\'85..", press enter. A web browser will open up to register the JDK feel free to register or close the browser.
\par 
\par Now java is done extracting we are going to set it up in the OS with the following commands.
\par \tab mv jdk1*/ /usr/local/
\par \tab ln -s /usr/local/jdk1* /usr/local/java
\par Java is now installed and is in a location we expect it to be in.
\par 
\par }{\b\f4\insrsid10294001 Tomcat Install
\par ------------------------------------------------------
\par }{\f4\insrsid10294001 You should already be in "/ust/local/oc/install" if not cd into it now via the command below.
\par \tab cd /usr/local/oc/install
\par Now run the following commands to install tomcat.
\par \tab tar -zxvf apache-tomcat-*
\par \tab mv apache-tomcat-6.0.32 /usr/local/
\par \tab ln -s /usr/local/apache-tomcat-6.0.32 /usr/local/tomcat
\par \tab /usr/sbin/adduser tomcat
\par Now we are going to move all the webapps that come with tomcat to an oldwebapps directory as we do not need them
\par \tab mkdir /usr/local/tomcat/oldwebapps 
\par \tab mv /usr/local/tomcat/webapps/* /usr/local/tomcat/oldwebapps
\par Tomcat is now installed, we will setup the init script we when run through the OpenClinica application setup.
\par 
\par }{\b\f4\insrsid10294001 Postgres install
\par ------------------------------------------------------
\par NOTE: If you are using oracle as your database please skip this section and install oracle now, we do not provide instructions on how to install oracle, we do provide instructio
ns later in this document that shows you how to setup the OpenClinica user and db within oracle so OpenClinica can use oracle.
\par 
\par }{\f4\insrsid10294001 You should already be in "/ust/local/oc/install" if not cd into it now via the command below.
\par \tab cd /usr/local/oc/install
\par \tab chmod a+x postgresql-8.4.*
\par \tab ./postgresql-8.4.* --mode text
\par 
\par Now you will see the PostgresSQL Setup Wizard start, for the most part we want the defaults, I have displayed them below, confirm they match and hit enter for each section is they do. If they do not match type in what I have in my examples below.
\par 
\par \tab Installation Directory [/opt/PostgreSQL/8.4]:  }{\b\f4\insrsid10294001 (press enter to accept this)
\par \tab }{\f4\insrsid10294001 Data Directory [/opt/PostgreSQL/8.4/data]: }{\b\f4\insrsid10294001 (press enter to accept this)
\par \tab }{\f4\insrsid10294001 Password : }{\b\f4\insrsid10294001 (enter the password for the postgres DB superuser, please keep this password you will need it again in this installation., then press enter)
\par \tab }{\f4\insrsid10294001 Retype password :}{\b\f4\insrsid10294001  (re-type the password you types in the previous step and press enter)
\par \tab }{\f4\insrsid10294001 Port [5432]: }{\b\f4\insrsid10294001 (press enter to accept this)
\par \tab }{\f4\insrsid10294001 Please choose an option [1] : }{\b\f4\insrsid10294001 (press enter to accept this)
\par \tab }{\f4\insrsid10294001 Install pl/pgsql in template1 database? [Y/n]:  }{\b\f4\insrsid10294001 (type "n" and press enter)
\par \tab }{\f4\insrsid10294001 Do you want to continue? [Y/n]:}{\b\f4\insrsid10294001  (press enter to accept this)
\par }{\f4\insrsid10294001 Setup will install postgres and you should see a "Setup has finished installing PostgreSQL on your computer." message. You will then have the following prompt.
\par \tab Stack Builder may be used to download and install additional tools, drivers and applications to complement your PostgreSQL installation. [Y/n]:  }{\b\f4\insrsid10294001 (type "n" and press enter)
\par \tab 
\par }{\f4\insrsid10294001 Postgres is now installed and will start on boot.}{\b\f4\insrsid10294001 
\par 
\par Setup OpenClinica application and db.
\par ------------------------------------------------------
\par }{\f4\insrsid10294001 You should already be in "/ust/local/oc/install" if not cd into it now via the command below.
\par \tab cd /usr/local/oc/install
\par \tab unzip OpenClinica-3.1*
\par \tab cd OpenClinica-3.1*/distribution
\par \tab unzip OpenClinica.war -d OpenClinica
\par \tab cp -rf OpenClinica* /usr/local/tomcat/webapps
\par \tab rm -f /usr/local/tomcat/webapps/OpenClinica.war
\par }{\b\f4\insrsid10294001 
\par \tab 
\par }{\f4\insrsid10294001 OpenClinica is now deployed we will configure it after we setup the databases. 
\par 
\par }{\b\f4\insrsid10294001 Postgres DB Setup
\par ------------------------------------------------------}{\f4\insrsid10294001 
\par When prompted for passwords on the below commands please enter the postgres superuser password you set during postgres install.
\par \tab /opt/PostgreSQL/8.4/bin/psql -U postgres -c "CREATE ROLE clinica LOGIN ENCRYPTED PASSWORD 'clinica' SUPERUSER NOINHERIT NOCREATEDB NOCREATEROLE" 
\par \tab /opt/PostgreSQL/8.4/bin/psql -U postgres -c "CREATE DATABASE  openclinica WITH ENCODING='UTF8' OWNER=clinica" 
\par 
\par These scripts created the db and the "clinic" db user OpenClinica uses to connect to the database. Note that the "clinic" db users password is set to "clinica" by default, since this is very insecure run the following commands to change the password.

\par 
\par \tab /opt/PostgreSQL/8.4/bin/psql -U postgres }{\b\f4\insrsid10294001 (this brings you to a psql prompt)
\par \tab }{\f4\insrsid10294001 ALTER USER clinica WITH PASSWORD 'XXXX; }{\b\f4\insrsid10294001 (replace XXXX with your wanted password, save this password it will be needed when we configure the OpenClinica application)
\par \tab }{\f4\insrsid10294001 \\q }{\b\f4\insrsid10294001 (this will exit the psql prompt)
\par }{\f4\insrsid10294001 \tab 
